The patient has a young adult who presented after trauma with proptosis and pain in the right eye, along with a visible bruising over the eye and forehead — classic signs suggestive of orbital floor or bony fracture. Traumatic proptosis due to orbital wall fracture commonly involves the sphenoid bone, especially given the proximity of the orbit to the posterior aspect of the maxilla and ethmoid/sphenoid sinuses. While other conditions like carotido-cavernous fistulas could cause similar features, they typically occur without direct trauma or bruising. The presence of localized soft tissue bruising further points toward blunt force trauma causing a skull base fracture rather than a spontaneous vascular event.

